==English==
===Etymology===
Middle English ''governaunce,'' from Middle French ''governance,'' from ''governer, gouverner'' to govern + ''-ance''
===Noun===
#the action or manner of governing; the fact that (a person, etc.) governs '''b.''' controlling, directing, or regulating influence; control, sway, mastery '''c.''' ''obsolete.'' in or under (a person's) governance: subject to his control. So to have, hold, take in governance '''d.''' ''obsolete.'' the state of being governed; good order; ''especially:'' in to set in governance 
#The office, function, or power of governing; authority or permission to govern; the command (of a body of men, a ship). '''b.''' ''obsolete.'' that which governs; governing person or body
#''obsolete.'' the manner in which something is governed or regulated; method of management, system of regulations; a rule of practice, a discipline
#Conduct of life or business; mode of living, behaviour, demeanour. ''also plural.'' proceedings, doings. '''b.''' ''obsolete.'' discreet or virtuous behaviour; wise self-command.

